\par NL:\tab This is tape three, side one, continuing our interview with Cantor Yehuda Mandel, March 17, 1982.  Yes, so, even before the Nazi occupation there was mounting antisemitism.
\par YM:\tab All the time.
\par NL:\tab All the time.
\par YM:\tab All the time.  If you look back to 1920, you know what happened in Hungary.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Hundreds of people were killed, and, and, eh, persecuted, then already, because they had that, they had that need to do something against the Jews.  Why?  The main reason in my opinion is, was, at that time, when everything was fine, was the 
Church.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab The Church, the Catholic Church had an immense influence.  The state religion was Catholic, and they had an immense influence on the people.  And I don't have to tell you that the Church did not do too much good for the Jews at any t
ime, and, ah...
\par NL:\tab Was there also an economic factor, Jews were the prime elements in the middle class I believe, weren't they?
\par YM:\tab Actually, yes.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Yes, that's true.  And jealousy.
\par NL:\tab Jealousy.
\par YM:\tab And, eh, was prevalent all the time, everywhere.
\par NL:\tab Hmm.
\par YM:\tab However, the time I'm talking about and which I experienced, it was already official.  There were laws passed by the parliament against the Jews, what I have told you before.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab So, do you think I should go back, eh, go on?
\par NL:\tab I think...
\par YM:\tab On my own, or shall I, eh, shall I continue, or do you have any questions concerning...
\par NL:\tab I was just going to ask one more question.  Were you aware of any large numbers of Jews leaving Hungary at this time, or talking about leaving?
\par YM:\tab If there were people who were leaving, it was a very, very minute, little, eh...
\par NL:\tab Group.
\par YM:\tab ...group, or percentage of the Jewish people.  Hungarian Jewry really could have saved itself, almost completely, if they would have been aware of what they are facing.
\par NL:\tab Where could they have gone, Mr. Mandel?
\par YM:\tab They could have gone to countries like Canada.  They could have gone to countries like, in a, in a limited way, even to Palestine of that time, and many, many other places.  But, everyone else, I thin
k, or most of the people, including myself, we never realized.  Finally, we had, we had it on the wall as they say.  It was just to be seen.  The picture was there.  Hundreds of, hundreds of people were leaving Germany, going through Hungary, going throug
h Yugoslavia...
\par NL:\tab You heard stories about the persecution.
\par YM:\tab From all facets of life, and we could have seen.  But most probably, and this is my own feeling, we didn't want to see it.  We had it too good.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Finally I, as a person 32 years old
, come to Budapest, and when my salary had to be established, so the Secretary General tells me, "We'll put you in this-and-this class, classification of salary scale," he says, "you know, this is the salary the Minister for Interior, for the Interior is 
g
etting, so you should be satisfied."  So we, we couldn't spend it, and we couldn't, as beautiful as we wanted to live, we just, we just had more than we could observe, or could use.  And this probably was one factor.  Finally, Austria was occupied, we saw
 it, we felt it, we, we saw it, we knew what happened in '39, we knew what happened in '38, we knew what happened in }{\i\fs24 Oberoestreich}{\fs24  [or }{\i\fs24 Ober\'f6streich}{\fs24 ] in '37, '38, '39, and we still stayed there.
\par NL:\tab You felt immune.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  It can be, can be anywhere and everywhere but here.  And this is the }{\i\fs24 klala}{\fs24 
, the curse, of Jews.  I, as I read on now and read all through the generations, we didn't understand.  Other people say we are smart.  I think we aren't so smart for ourselves anyway.
\par NL:\tab When it comes to survival.
\par YM:\tab Right.  Any more questions?
\par NL:\tab Not, not at the moment.  And so you decided to go to London, then, or did you...
\par YM:\tab I applied, and I got an answer very quickly, "Yes, we, we are happy to have you for this and this Shabbat," and I should come.
\par NL:\tab So this was '37.
\par YM:\tab End of '37, yes.  Or the beginning of '38, '37-'38.  I think it was February of '38 if I am not wrong.  I went to London.  I was introduced to the Chief Rabbi and the }{\i\fs24 Bet Din}{\fs24  [Rabbinical Court] was si
tting with me for all morning, and I went through the, the eh, tests which they give there, because there, they, if you are engaged by the United Synagogue, it's for a lifetime.  So they are very careful with their engagements, and who they engage, and ho
w, and so on.
\par NL:\tab May I ask what language you spoke?
\par YM:\tab Yiddish.
\par NL:\tab Yiddish.
\par YM:\tab Or, with the }{\i\fs24 Bet Din}{\fs24  I spoke Hebrew.
\par NL:\tab Hebrew.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  Eh, and, I couldn't, I didn't speak a word of English, so how could I speak any other language but Yiddish?
\par NL:\tab Well, I, I wondered.
\par YM:\tab Yiddish with the people in general.  For instance, I stayed in a hotel, so the owner of the hotel was very honored that the Duke's Place Synagogue sends to him the }{\i\fs24 hazan}{\fs24 
 and so forth, he himself served everything I needed, but he spoke in perfect Yiddish, so no problem.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab With eh, Rabbi, eh...
\par NL:\tab Hertz.
\par YM:\tab Hertz.  I don't know if you know it, that he was born and in childhood lived in Hungary.
\par NL:\tab No, I didn't.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  And he remembered a few Hungarian words.
\par NL:\tab [chuckles]
\par YM:\tab So that was our little joke.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab So, eh, I went through the whole thing, the United Synagogue sent me for medical exams and all that, and finally, after I performed services and after they felt I may be a candidate, and this again bears out 
what I said before, we just didn't realize what we are faced with.  There were two meetings of the very selected board of the United Synagogue.  Sir Waley Cohen was the president, and some other people, four or five that I remember, one Dr. Rosen, who was
 the vice president of Duke's Place Temple, he was with me because he spoke Yiddish and in a hurry, if I had to say something, he was the man who translated my Yiddish into English.  But anyway, what I want to say is, I performed services }{\i\fs24 
Shabbes}{\fs24 .  Monday, 
Tuesday, were taken up with seeing the doctors, getting through the health examinations, and all that, in the afternoon have meetings with the board of the United Synagogue, and Wednesday, and they prepared the agreement, and we are supposed to sign it on
 
Wednesday evening.  Fine.  Wednesday morning I receive a telegram from Eppler Shambur [phonetic], he was the executive vice president of the main organiz-, main community in Budapest, "Your papers are in order again for another four years.  We expect you 
home.  With love."
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab My family is in Budapest.  We are beautifully, eh...
\par NL:\tab Situated.
\par YM:\tab ...situated, and I go to the United Synagogue main office, and tell the secretary to call Sir Waley Cohen for me.  I couldn't talk to hi
m, so I asked him, he spoke Yiddish, too, to translate and tell the, eh, president, Sir Waley Cohen, that I am again well-situated in Hungary and I am leaving, I don't want them to bear any expenses, I will go back home.  And I went back in 1938 to Hungar
y.  So did we see?  We were just blind.  We didn't realize what's going on.
\par NL:\tab But you may have thought there was a change in the atmosphere inasmuch...
\par YM:\tab I, yes.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab I surely did.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab But it wasn't so.  And I was--I didn't see clearly.
\par NL:\tab Well...
\par YM:\tab Our eyes were completely--in Yiddish they say, }{\i\fs24 Oz Got vil einem schtroffen, nemt em zu dem ruyabid}{\fs24 . [If God wants to punish someone, then his capacity of seeing is taken away.]  The capacity of seeing.
\par NL:\tab Of seeing.
\par YM:\tab And this is exactly what happened to Hungarians.
\par NL:\tab But what did happen that seemed to indicate a change in the atmosphere?  Was it a freak or a fluke?
\par YM:\tab When I came back, the parliament was discussing the second law against the Jews.  That's the way it was.  In 1939, I stayed there with all kinds of trouble, here and there, again some, eh...
\par NL:\tab Restrictions.
\par YM:\tab ...some restrictions, and here I won't be able maybe you know to perform services again, and this news came, and went, and came, and went, but you have to under
stand that the community as such had an immense power, an immense power.  In spite of everything.
\par NL:\tab Political?
\par YM:\tab Political and locally.  Even with this antisemite who was the head of the Alien Department, even through somebody else they had influence on him.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab And I stayed on.  The first, the first, eh...
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, but was your son feeling some discrimination in school?
\par YM:\tab No, because he was all, among all Jewish children.
\par NL:\tab He was in a Jewish school.
\par YM:\tab In a Jewish school.
\par NL:\tab I see.  And your wife, was she teaching?
\par YM:\tab She was not teaching, and she didn't feel it.
\par NL:\tab She didn't feel it.
\par YM:\tab Here and there you heard the [unclear].
\par NL:\tab But it was tolerable.
\par YM:\tab Or outside, I don't know, you saw something of this, but it wasn't an organized way of hurting Jews.  However, it seems, through the Alien Department of the Ministry of the Interior, I was drafted into the, eh, into the labor camp in 1939 already.

\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab During the summer we were in a place for the summer.
\par NL:\tab Resort.
\par YM:\tab Resort.  I received a, I received from the Ministry of Interior to report so and so here and here at this and this time.  I knew it is no good, because this is the way they gathered the people who were later on, trans-,
\par NL:\tab Transported.
\par YM:\tab Transported to, deported to Kamenets-Pudolsk.  I went home, and spoke to the organization, mainly to this executive vice president, who spoke to the chief rabbinate of Hungary.  We had a wonderful person.  His name was Dr. Havashi, Shimon\endash 
Simon Havashi.  And he said the following, "Look, you had difficulty already because you are a Czechoslovakian citizen.  How about if we do this?  I will call the organization of chaplaincy."  The Jews had chaplain
s just as the Catholics had chaplains.  "You are qualified.  You are }{\i\fs24 musmach}{\fs24  of }{\i\fs24 yeshivah}{\fs24 
 [master, authority].  President.  We will write up your whole history.  I myself will contact the minister for military..." For, eh, I don't know what it was, [mumbles].
\par NL:\tab Military affairs.
\par YM:\tab Military affairs.  "And try to make a deal to them.  You will serve as a chaplain in the Hungarian army."  Wonderful.  Very good.  So this happened.  I was accepted.  I went into the army, instead of being herded up and, I don'
t know, wherever they wanted to take me.
\par NL:\tab To the Russian front.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  And I worked there as a chaplain.  I stayed in my position, but whenever there was any question of, of Jew-, I mean, anything to do with Jewish chaplaincy, I was there in the hospi
tals, in the barracks, military barracks.  If there was any other question...
\par NL:\tab If someone died.
\par YM:\tab If someone died, or funeral, or even weddings and so on, I, I was the one.
\par NL:\tab You moved around.
\par YM:\tab Moved, moved around.  But I kept my position and stayed in Budapest.
\par NL:\tab Ohhhhh...
\par YM:\tab In and around Budapest.  I did not go away.  I did not have to leave my position.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab 'Cause that was one condition of, eh...
\par NL:\tab Your appointment.
\par YM:\tab Of my appointment, that the chief rabbi said, "He has a hi
gh position here and is needed here.  However, he will serve wherever you need him, whenever you need him.  He is at your disposal.  We have in the whole country two or three chaplains, and we can't get you more.  We don't have the people, but here is you
r chance."  So, they agreed.  So, here it went on...
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, did you have contact with other Jews in the labor force, and could you see what was happening?
\par YM:\tab This was not the labor force yet.  At the time when I went...
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par YM:\tab ...in '39, Jews were still in the military.
\par NL:\tab This was the army.
\par YM:\tab The army.
\par NL:\tab And you had a Hungarian army uniform.
\par YM:\tab Ya.
\par NL:\tab I see.  I see.
\par YM:\tab Later on, this went on 1939, '40, I t
hink even '41, then came a decree, a military decree, "Jews cannot wear Hungarian uniforms anymore, and have to be demoted."  If they were officers, they were demoted to privates, put into the, into different companies, labor companies.
\par NL:\tab Labor companies.
\par YM:\tab Labor companies.  And, there were people for instance who were high, highly, eh...
\par NL:\tab In high ranks.
\par YM:\tab In high ranks.  They couldn't keep their distinction in any way, and had to be demoted as laborers.  Even this didn't open our eyes.  I think ve
ry few people escaped after this.  I could have, for instance, and I'm not going far away, I'm just talking about myself, because the others were better and well-versed than I was.  I was at the time a Czechoslovakian citizen, a Czechoslovakian citizen.  
As a Czechoslo-, the Czechoslovakian, the Hungarian quota, the Rumanian quota was filled with a waiting list for the United States to, to get in for years and years.  But the Czechoslovakian quota, for reasons of course, because very few immigrants...

\par NL:\tab Left.
\par YM:\tab Very few left Czechoslovakia.  It was a beautiful, wonderful little country.
\par NL:\tab Few applied.
\par YM:\tab Few applied.  And I could have come here in 1938 or '39 without waiting a day, just leave my things there and get out.  But I didn't do it.  We just didn't believe it.
\par NL:\tab But you see, you had three or four years of relatively calm life.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  This is what kept me there, and kept everyone there.  They told the joke that, I don't know, an aunt or mother or grandmother is the--sacrificed herself for a
 piece of furniture, because she couldn't leave that.  Or the dining room, or the this.  And this was all true.  And I, I'm taking the examples of...
\par NL:\tab This is, I'm afraid, human nature, not just Jewish.
\par YM:\tab Of myself.  Ya.  So, I stayed and in 1939, fro
m 1939 until about '41, the end of '41, something like that, I served as a chaplain of the Hungarian army, as a Jew, Jewish chaplain.  After this, when everyone else was demoted, I was demoted myself.  The only distinction we had was this cap that you see
 on that picture.
\par NL:\tab Picture.
\par YM:\tab Ya, picture.  And we worked as laborers.  For the first, '42, '43, and even part of '44, I was never over the border, let's say, not in Poland, not in...
\par NL:\tab Russia.
\par YM:\tab ...Galicia, not in Russia.  In 1944, March the 19th,
 the Germans occupied Hungary.  And then, of course, the screws were tightened and tightened.  The Jewish Committee was established, and this and that, and later on, as you, as you have seen probably from the Joel Brand}{\fs24\super 10{\footnote 
\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx-1440\tx-1080\tx-720\tx-360\tx0\tx360\tx1080\tx1800\tx2520\tx3240\tx3960\tx4680\tx5400\tx6120\tx6840\tx7560\tx7920\tx8280\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {10}{
\fs24   }{Brand, J., and A. Weissberg, }{\ul Desperate Mission: Joel Brand's Story}{.  New York, 1958.}}}{\fs24 
 book and so on, the details I won't go in, because this is public knowledge.  In June, a group finally--the way it went and how, is very well described, I think in Joel's book.  A group of about 1700 J
ews, the outstanding, leading Jews of Hungary, were gathered together, and with German permission, left Hungary to go to Palestine, to Israel.  The motivation were the trucks, of course, which he expected to get, and all that, but this is history, so I wo
n't go into that.
\par NL:\tab Could we go back a little,
\par YM:\tab Sure.
\par NL:\tab I think it would be very important for us to hear about your experiences in the labor battalions between '42 and '44, if you would tell us where you were.
\par YM:\tab In the labor battalions I was, I remember the first one, I was in--let me write this down for you...
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab ...because it's Hungarian.  This was the first camp.  Let me write it here.  Eh, probably 1940.  1940, it was Laplo Danya [phonetic].
\par NL:\tab Not far from Budapest.
\par YM:\tab Eh, no, about, let's say, about 100km, something like that.  The same year, yes, I have to say it, while I was even in labor camp I was always taken out or...
\par NL:\tab Repatriated?
\par YM:\tab ...forced out by the community of Budapest, that I got a permit for this Shabbat and that Shabbat.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab And }{\i\fs24 Rosh Hodesh}{\fs24  and High Holy days, of course, and wherever I was, I could always come home and perform those services.
\par NL:\tab I see.  The authorities, respected that?
\par YM:\tab The authorities respected it because the command 
came from higher up place given to this lower command, and I went up.  Eh, in the labor camp itself, I had many, many people who knew me from home, but I tried, and I did, not take anything to be different for me than for anybody else.  If the wheel barro
w had to be carried, I carried it like everybody else.  I was strong.  There was nothing wrong with me.  I was a healthy, strong, comparatively young person, so I worked on with everybody else.
\par NL:\tab What kinds of work did the battalions do?
\par YM:\tab We built so-called, eh, }{\i\fs24 Flugplatz}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab Fortifications?
\par YM:\tab No, no, eh, airports.
\par NL:\tab Airports.  }{\i\fs24 Flugplatz}{\fs24 .
\par YM:\tab Which were never used, and they knew it would never be used.  But in order to keep us occupied, and to take the last drop of strength out of us, of course, th
is was done.  We worked in another place, Bilka [phonetic], 1943, probably, Bilka.  1943 is, eh, that was a stone...
\par NL:\tab Quarry.
\par YM:\tab Quarry, ya.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Eh, I don't remember now the name.
\par NL:\tab It will come.
\par YM:\tab Ya.
\par NL:\tab It will come.
\par YM:\tab So...
\par NL:\tab And, the Hungarians themselves were in charge, or were there some German overseers?
\par YM:\tab [unclear] the, up to 1944, there were no Germans.  Eh, the Hungarian military was in charge.  In each company there were two-hundred-and either sixteen or twenty-six Jews who had no worth [?] or "work"?] whatsoever.
\par NL:\tab No-
\par YM:\tab No worth of command or anything.  Eh, to each of these companies, nine hundred, two-hundred-and-sixteen or -twenty people, there were twenty-four milit-, eh, milit-, I mean soldiers, Hungarian soldiers
, non-Jews, who had ammunition and had, and they were our guards.  They guarded us.  There was a commander for each...
\par NL:\tab Unit.
\par YM:\tab Unit.  And a sub-commander for each unit.  If we were lucky enough to have a person with who
m we could talk, especially if it was a person, like I had one, for instance, who was an official in a bank.  So I used to deal with that bank and I knew him from before.  So I had some influence on him.  However, if there was one like we had in this plac
e, Bilka, who wanted us to run eh, for six, eight miles, and people were just fainting, he could do that.  He was sitting in his little car and chasing us.  Which car was behind us...
\par NL:\tab Just maliciously.
\par YM:\tab Just maliciously, for no good reason.
\par NL:\tab No good reason.
\par YM:\tab No.  Now, I myself was in many cases, because of my position probably in the community, employed as or rather assigned to be--because I had this training, I think I mentioned to you, from the Czechoslovakian army yet, that I took the courses
 for male nursing, I was assigned to be the nurse.  This gave me a very good opportunity.  In Hungary it was no problem, but then we worked, for instance, in Bilka, which was already a Ruthenian, eh, district, so I could talk to the people who lived there
, and here and there I heard the radio and brought back to my, to the other Jewish people some news.
\par NL:\tab Some news.
\par YM:\tab Some news from Bilka.  The whole process of the labor camp was unhuman.  And I remember particularly one case when we went the first time
, we went over the border of Hungary, a sergeant major told us, "Don't think that we are taking you from here to bring you back.  You Jews should know what you are--what you are faced with."  That was in '44.  Of course, we knew already anyway what we are
 
faced with.  The Hungarian population, with the exception of a very few, was antisemitic.  They didn't have to be coaxed into hating the Jew.  They were brought up on that.  The young boy who grew up with the church where he went every Sunday and he heard
 from the priest, "Now we will celebrate the holiday which will bring back the birth of our Christ, who was killed by..." and that went on and on and on, and all kinds of other things.
\par NL:\tab What other work did the Jews do in the labor battalions besides help to build aircraft, or airfields.
\par YM:\tab Airfields.  They were in stone...
\par NL:\tab Quarries.
\par YM:\tab ...quarries.  They were in coal mines.  They were in--no field work, because a Jew, a Jew later on, '40, '41, '42, after the Jewish laws were passed, couldn't even ta
lk to a non-Jew in a community if there was, let's say a kindhearted old lady who wanted to give these Jewish workers, laborers, some bread or some milk, to sell them, for good money.  She couldn't do it.  If you were caught, you were extremely punished.

\par NL:\tab Punished.
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab Severely.
\par YM:\tab Severely.
\par NL:\tab Digging ditches, I suppose.
\par YM:\tab Digging ditches, later on.  That was already 1944, when the Germans thought that they would save themselves by, eh, by having those ditches and...
\par NL:\tab Tanks.
\par YM:\tab ...tanks won't come through.
\par NL:\tab Anti-tank ditches.
\par YM:\tab Crazy things.  And, eh...
\par NL:\tab So many Jews perished...
\par YM:\tab Many, many.
\par NL:\tab ...in this, in these, years.
\par YM:\tab And many Jews were killed.
\par NL:\tab And many were killed.
\par YM:\tab Sure, in the labor camps.  If you couldn't work any longer.
\par NL:\tab You were killed.
\par YM:\tab Done away with.  That's it.
\par NL:\tab Were you given enough...
\par YM:\tab Food.
\par NL:\tab ...food to sustain?  No.
\par YM:\tab We were given food.  To some people, they could survive on it.  Some people just faded away on it, because it was no food of any value, of any...
\par NL:\tab Did you live in barracks, [unclear].
\par YM:\tab We lived, as a rule, not in barracks, but in, in places where animals were placed for, what would that be,
\par NL:\tab Preserves?
\par YM:\tab Stables.  No.
\par NL:\tab Oh, stables.
\par YM:\tab Stables, ya.  Now we are at 1944.
\par NL:\tab One more question...
\par YM:\tab Ya.
\par NL:\tab ...please, eh, Cantor.  Did you have any contact with your family during '43 and '44?
\par YM:\tab Yes.  I did, and not only that, but because of the strength of the community and the heavy influence they had on certain poli-
\par NL:\tab Certain politicians.
\par YM:\tab Eh, I was always home, let's say for }{\i\fs24 Pesach}{\fs24 , for }{\i\fs24 Rosh Hashanah}{\fs24 , for }{\i\fs24 Yom Kippur}{\fs24 , for }{\i\fs24 Shavuot}{\fs24 , for, a
nd many, in many years, many of these years, and we are talking now from '39 through '44, it's five years almost, there were times when we were discharged.  The whole company was discharged because it was snow and ice and so on, and it wasn't even, not ev
en an excuse could be found why they are keeping us there.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par 
