\par NL:\tab This is a continuation of the deferred interview with Cantor Yehuda Mandel.  This is June 4, 1982, and we'll now continue from the other portion of the tape.
  Yes, Cantor Mandel, would you like to add to the material you've already told us about in connection with this last experience?
\par YM:\tab In great strokes, I would like to say the following.  1944, October the 15th, as you probably remember, Horthy, the Hungarian, eh...
\par NL:\tab Regent.
\par YM:\tab Regent, somehow or other got together with the Allied Forces and made a declaration, and through his Ministry of the, of the, Exterior, as they called it there, he made a decision to which it seems the government, the ministers, 
at the time, agreed, or didn't agree, but it seems it was without the knowledge of the Germans...
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab ...who were at the time already, of course, in Hungary...
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab ...because they came in the 18th of March, or 19th of March, 1944.  He made up his mind that he will declare Hungary joining the Allied Forces, and he did that...
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab ...on the 15th of, eh...
\par NL:\tab October.
\par YM:\tab ...October.
\par NL:\tab Now, excuse me, may we just step back, because there's a very important segment, and I w
ondered if you, in the places where you were, were aware of the change.  I'm not sure if I'm pronouncing the name of the head of the Arrow Cross, but in the fall, late August or early September of '44, the Arrow Cross movement came into control under Sz
\'e1lasi.
\par YM:\tab Sz\'e1lasi.
\par NL:\tab Sz\'e1lasi.
\par YM:\tab Sz\'e1lasi is the proper pronunciation.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  Now were you aware of that, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab Eh, no.
\par NL:\tab No.
\par YM:\tab Not at all.  We knew--we weren't aware of Auschwitz, we weren't because we were kept away from everything.  And even if we stole somewhere a little news, it was just that controlled news which the Hungarian or, eh...
\par NL:\tab The Germans.
\par YM:\tab ...or German stations disseminated.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab ...to us.  So we weren't aware of anything.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab We were terribly scared, and lived under that constant fear of being killed, because we were told time and again by the Hungarian guards who were with us that we weren't brought here to be taken back eventually home, or to, or to get through...

\par NL:\tab Survive.
\par YM:\tab ...this period, or to survive.  We were brought here to eradicate us, to }{\i\fs24 erase}{\fs24  us, they used the expression.
\par NL:\tab }{\i\fs24 They}{\fs24  told you that.
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab So...
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab So this was the Hungarians, not the Germans.
\par YM:\tab The Hungarians.
\par NL:\tab Not the Germans.
\par YM:\tab I have to say one more thing about the German and Hungarian guards.  That the hatred, or rather the, the, ed-, education these poor peasants were given, and 
the antisemitism which was pushed into many of them by force, that they were just filled with hatred, and they killed, so to say, like it would be a }{\i\fs24 mitzvah}{\fs24 
 [good deed] to be performed.  The German killed when he had an order to kill.  The Hungarian peasant boy who came in, and we had, in a company there were about 224 people, there were, there was a guard to every four men.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab Can you imagine what that is?
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab We couldn't move, we couldn't go, we couldn't look, unless we had a guard along with us.
\par NL:\tab And about how many Jews were there in the whole, eh, assemblage?
\par YM:\tab Each, oh, there were, at times there were presumably more than 125,000 in, called in for work, for...
\par NL:\tab In the labor force.
\par YM:\tab ...in the labor force.  And, and, and, eh, to be detained in detention for...
\par NL:\tab So the attrition rate must have been very heavy.
\par YM:\tab Immense.  Immense.
\par NL:\tab Beatings and outright shootings.
\par YM:\tab For instance, four brother-in-laws, my first wife's two brothers and two brother-in-laws, were--died at the }{\i\fs24 Duna}{\fs24\super 11{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar
\tx-1440\tx-1080\tx-720\tx-360\tx0\tx360\tx1080\tx1800\tx2520\tx3240\tx3960\tx4680\tx5400\tx6120\tx6840\tx7560\tx7920\tx8280\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {11}{\fs24   }{
Hungarian name for Danube River.}}}{\fs24  [phonetic], on }{\i\fs24 Flecktyphus}{\fs24  [typhus], on starvation, on, eh, I don't know...
\par NL:\tab Beatings.
\par YM:\tab Beatings, and so on.  So this was the, this was the trend.
\par NL:\tab Great mortality.
\par YM:\tab This was the trend.  So, it is very hard to say, if we were informed or not.  If we are talking about the normal, human approach to information, we never had it.  We never, we heard something, we came to a spot where, where there were in the C
arpathian Mountains, people who escaped to the, Czechoslova-, to the Slovakian freedom fighters, so we heard something that, for instance, M\'e1
ramarossziget, which was a heavily Jewish, populated Jewish town, there are no more Jews.  We couldn't understand, 
what is he talking about?  How can this be?  So, eh, but to come back to what I can say as a fact, when we heard, the Horthy declaration, we did hear, and we were at the time in Poland, yet, somewhere in Galicia, I don't remember exactly where.
\par NL:\tab Part of your labor, work?
\par YM:\tab Part of the labor force, part of the company, let's say where we were, where I was, there we heard, somehow, either I or somebody else brought the news that Horthy made this and this declaration.
\par NL:\tab Now, one more interruption, please.
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab What were you doing, what was Hungary doing in Poland?  Was this on German orders?
\par YM:\tab Of course.  Hungarian Jews were organized into labor battalions and taken first, as I have mentioned previously, to work in Hungary, no sense at all, to build, I don't know, eh, places for...
\par NL:\tab Ditches.
\par YM:\tab Ditches.  For, na-, air, airf-, air, eh...
\par NL:\tab Fields.
\par YM:\tab ...fields.  We knew in advance, and everybody knew that there will never be an airfield there, because it just didn't make sense.  But just...
\par NL:\tab Made work.
\par YM:\tab ...to make us work.
\par NL:\tab And then Poland?
\par YM:\tab No, then we were pushed and pushed and pushed, at German orders, of course, further out, so we got to Galicia, we got to Pol-, we got to Poland, we got to the Russian part, Ru
ssian Poland, and so on.  And my whole family, members of my family died there, no one came back.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab From there.  These were the young people of the family.  The others went to Auschwitz, of course.  Now, when we heard, and maybe I skipped a little bit because it could just be repetition over and over again.
\par NL:\tab It's all right.  It's all very important.
\par YM:\tab So, the way we lived was just exactly what I told you.  That the Hungarian soldiers were constantly around us, pushing us, beating us, killing
 us, all kinds of things, and they told us that that's what we are there for.  When the Horthy declaration, October the 15th, finally came out, we were all elated.
\par NL:\tab Of course.
\par YM:\tab And we tried very hard to get together, to organize ourselves, to be able
 to go back to home, so to say.  We didn't know what happened in Budapest, we didn't know that almost none of our, eh, of our family members are in Budapest anymore.  My own family was already long ago in Bergen-Belsen, and others were in the same place o
r in Auschwitz, or were destroyed already, or--the good thing was if they got into the ghetto, which was already organized in, eh, much earlier, in 1944.  So...
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, but if they had gone into the ghetto, you say, they stood a better chance of surviving?
\par YM:\tab In most cases, yes.  At least at the beginning.  Of course, you have to understand that in the ghetto, ya, I have to, I have to reflect to what you have said before, and maybe it will be a little mixed up.
\par NL:\tab That's all right.
\par YM:\tab But don't mind me.
\par NL:\tab We'll come, eh...
\par YM:\tab It's too excit-, too much excitement for me to talk about it, but I am happy to put it down, and...
\par NL:\tab I'm sorry, if it's distressing.
\par YM:\tab No, that's perfectly all right.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab When we heard the Horthy declaration, I'm coming back to this the third time.
\par NL:\tab I'm not letting you finish [chuckles].
\par YM:\tab We, we, no, we thought we will, we will go home.  We didn't know about what happened, about ghetto, about this, that, nothing.  So, it was good.  That was the 15th.  I think, just a few hours later, we heard that Sz\'e1
lasi took over, the Germans clamped down on the Hungarians, the Hungarian government...
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab ...helped Sz\'e1lasi.  Sz\'e1lasi became, eh, the, eh...
\par NL:\tab The head of government?
\par YM:\tab Prime minister, the head of the government, so to say.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab And he was the antisemite...
\par NL:\tab Par excellence.
\par YM:\tab Arch antisemite.  And there, he organized, because military forces he didn't have any more, so he organized the youngsters, the 15, 16, 17-year-old boys, every
one had a, a gun, and sent them into the ghetto houses.  You remember that, eh, through him...
\par NL:\tab Wallenberg.
\par YM:\tab Through Wallenberg, these so-called }{\i\fs24 gesch\'fctzteHa\'fcser}{\fs24  [protected houses] 
were organized.  They went in there, took out the people, they took them in the morning, they never came back, as they had promised in the evening.  They lined them up in the, in the courtyards, whoever they wanted they took, they took them on the street,
 they took them to the Danube.  Hundreds of people were murdered by being shot into the Danube.  Just shot at the, at the, eh, at the, eh, close to the...
\par NL:\tab Shore.
\par YM:\tab ...shore, and thrown into the water.  And that was life in Budapest.  At the time I was
 still--ya, I came back, now this happened probably October the 16th, 17th, something like that.  But, this organization took place in the labor battalion, or rather, the Germans gave an order as the Russians pushed back in the direction to, towards Hunga
ry, that all the labor forces must be marched in the direction of, eh, Austria, or rather, Germany, and well, if you couldn't march, you just, eh...
\par NL:\tab Died.
\par YM:\tab ...died, or was killed.  So, we, about 20 or 22 of us, got together, and we got as far from Budapest, a place called, eh, S\'e1toralja\'fajhely.
\par NL:\tab Would you spell that?
\par YM:\tab S-A-T-
\par NL:\tab T?
\par YM:\tab T, like Thomas, O-R-, eh, let me write it down, it's easier I think than to spell it, [mumbles, spelling it], Sator-alja-ujhely\endash that place I will--ujhely.
\par NL:\tab You escaped from your guards, then, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab Yes, yes.  We escaped and walked nights, because daytime was dangerous.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab We, if we could, somehow, we got a little lift by a peasant who drove in some direction, a car, or something, and so we got
, as I say, it took us, the 17th, I remember, I arrived in Budapest the 7th of November, 1944.  So it took us close to three weeks to make 210 or 250km.  Finally...
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, did you have any Jewish insignia on that would have identified you?
\par YM:\tab No, we tore it all off.
\par NL:\tab You tore it off.
\par YM:\tab And walked without it, and slept in the fields.  And I will never forget it, when I came to a town which is just on the outskirts of Budapest, I saw in the Hungar-, on the Hungarian paper, on the top of the pape
r, that the fall of Budapest is expected within the shortest while.  So we pushed on, and got into Budapest, and I got in, I didn't think what I'm doing at the time, probably, I wasn't just careful enough, but I went back to our apartment, which was on Ve
s
herlaynu [phonetic], 13.  It was about two-and-a-half blocks, three blocks, away from my temple, and, um, I went up, that was the 7th of November, terrible snow, we had a magnificent apartment, corner, it was a corner apartment looking out to two streets 
o
f Vesherlaynu, and eh, Kazinsi [phonetic] Street.  In the apartment, there were, presumably, because I have never seen them there, they were all over the place when I came down, and scattered all over, presumably 105 people were pushed into our apartment,
 which was a huge apartment, but still.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab They were laying like sardines.  I had a magnificent private library, among other things.  My son just told me this week, he was here to visit us with his family, so he told me that for his last birthday,
 which is the 8th of May, he got from his wife and children the }{\i\fs24 Encyclopaedia Judaica}{\fs24 , and I started to cry.  Why?  Because in the '20's, or was it the beginning of the '30's, the }{\i\fs24 Encyclopaedia Judaica}{\fs24 
 appeared first in Germany,
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab And I was one of the first subscribers, and I had, I don't remember now, was it, eight or nine volumes at the time already in my library, }{\i\fs24 Herrenzimmer}{\fs24  as we called it there, office.  And, eh...
\par NL:\tab What had happened to the library?
\par YM:\tab Not, not, not to talk about Shass and Poskim [phonetic] and so on, what I accumulated.  What happened?  Most probably it was used for wood.
\par NL:\tab Fuel.
\par YM:\tab To keep themselves alive.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.  Oh my.  Oh my.
\par YM:\tab Alive.  And these books were all used up.  I came in...
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab We were on the top floor.  There was no roof.  Snow was falling on the Persian rugs...
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab I saw the dining room, the magnificent }{\i\fs24 deutsche}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Tischlermeister}{\fs24  [German master carpenter] dining room, knocked to pieces, the Rosenthal...
\par NL:\tab China.
\par YM:\tab China, knocked to pieces, two or three pieces remained...
\par NL:\tab Oh my, oh my.
\par YM:\tab And, I thought I will get a heart attack.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab I didn't know what happened to my family, even then!  So...
\par NL:\tab Did you know any of the people in the room?
\par YM:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab No one.
\par YM:\tab No.  I could not get to anyone.
\par NL:\tab Just shoved in the room.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  Our, ya. Our superintendent in the house was a non-Jew, and mainly the woman, his wife, was a terrible antisemite, who, a child of my brother was brought to us, thinking, fr
om Yugoslavia, thinking maybe Budapest, you know, with my influence, and this and this, maybe he will be able to save because father and mother wasn't there anymore, so the grandparents sent the child to Budapest to us, and this antisemitic woman reported
 this chi-...
\par NL:\tab Child.
\par YM:\tab Child, who was then maybe six years old.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab That he's here, and he doesn't even talk Hungarian, and he came without permission, and to be taken away.  So, before anything happens, my wife, may she rest in peace, she 
sent him back to Yugoslavia, and he went, of course, to Auschwitz with the grandparents.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab So, this kind of thing.  But I didn't know about all this.  So the only, so, I was away about half a block from my...
\par NL:\tab Temple.
\par YM:\tab Temple, no, from t
he administrative building of our congregation.  I went out there.  There were some people who I knew very well, and they told me in short what has happened.  They, that, eh, select group of close to 2,000 people went with Dr., what's his name?
\par NL:\tab Kasztner.
\par YM:\tab 
Kas, Kasztner.  And, they, they don't know exactly where they are, but Kasztner has an office, he's here and here and here.  I couldn't go there either, because it was dangerous to even to breathe on the outside.  So I went to another place.  Finall
y I found some friends who told me what has happened, and that my family is together with those people who were taken, presumably, to Palestine.
\par NL:\tab That was the story.
\par YM:\tab That was the story.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.  But actually to Bergen-Belsen.
\par YM:\tab Actually they were, there were all kinds, I read, I just read, what's his name?
\par NL:\tab Brand.
\par YM:\tab Brand's book, and there, from that I see that no one knew exactly what will happen.  There were moments, my wife told me later on when we met after the war in Is
rael, that there were hours, days, when they thought they are being sent to Auschwitz, just like everybody, like the others.
\par NL:\tab That special Kasztner...
\par YM:\tab That special Kasztner group.
\par NL:\tab For which they had to pay a lot of money.  Yes.
\par YM:\tab Hundreds\endash millions.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab So, jewelry, or whatever anyone had, had to give.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  So, people were not sure what was going to happen to them, even on that transfer.
\par YM:\tab No, absolutely not.  Absolutely not.
\par NL:\tab It's a very important fact to note.
\par YM:\tab Yes, eh, no, never were they sure what's coming next.  But how did I find out finally what's with my family?  I went into one of these houses, which presumably were...  
\par NL:\tab Protected.
\par YM:\tab Pro-, protected.  And a very dear friend of mine, may he rest in peace, Dr. H
ershkowich, who was a rabbi in Budapest, told me, "Look, I can't tell you a thing, because what I know, I tell you.  But I think you must make it your business to get together, as hard as it is, we will dress you up as a Hungarian peasant, and we'll give 
y
ou this and that," eh, I had a big mustache, "and, you go on the street and we will give you papers," of course, false papers, "where we will say you are a, a, you are, eh, coming from the front, and you are injured, and this and that, and you are on furl
ough."  So, finally the third or fourth day I think, the third day after I arrived in Budapest, I got to the office of Dr. eh...
\par NL:\tab Kasztner.
\par YM:\tab Kasztner.  I don't blame him now, looking back in that he was extremely careful.  His secretary didn't want to
 receive me, I told her who I am, who I was, rather, and I'm interested to know one thing, to hear one thing from him, can he tell me where my family is at this time?  With my family was, besides our own son, the son, my brother's, eh, my bro-, my brother
'
s brother-in-law's child, who came up because his mother was caught on the street and, she was in Auschwitz, taken to Auschwitz immediately, so this poor child knew that when there was anything, they went up to Ellami, near to Aunt Ella, so this child wan
d
ered up to our apartment, and so when it was decided that my family will be taken, my wife said, "This child must be taken too.  I can't leave him here."  So she took him along.  So I wanted to know what happened.  I didn't even know that this child is wi
th her, but I was interested in my wife, my son, my brother.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab And, eh, I went up, after a lot of difficulties...
\par NL:\tab He didn't want to see you?
\par YM:\tab He didn't want to see me.  I had to go the next day, again.
\par NL:\tab You had to go back again?
\par YM:\tab Back again, endangering my life.  Finally, when I came...
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, but why didn't he want to see you?
\par YM:\tab Most probably, most probably the way I look back now, he did not want from anyone to give the information to anyone so that it shouldn't be publici
zed that someone spoke to him and given the exact information, because everyone else will be around with the same question.  So, somehow I could, I can see it in that view, in, in, eh...
\par NL:\tab Retrospect.
\par YM:\tab Ya, now.  But it was a terrible thing at the time.
\par NL:\tab He had a secretary.
\par YM:\tab He had a secretary, and she said, "No, you can't see him."  She told me all kinds of things, that there are German soldiers in here, officers, and he's discussing something, he's in conference, what.  Anyway,
\par NL:\tab But he was being protected, obviously.
\par YM:\tab He was being protected.  The next day, or whenever I got back, maybe it was the same day because I almost, you can't imagine...
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par YM:\tab ...what kind of des-
\par NL:\tab Desperation.
\par YM:\tab ...desperation I was in.  I wen
t back, and the secretary started the same story again.  I pushed her aside and I told her, "Look, I am coming from where, from where life doesn't have too much of a value anyhow.  I have nothing and no one here.  My family is gone and I know they are und
er the guidance of this--presumably--organization."  And pushed her aside, opened the door to Kasztner's office, and went in.  And he started giving me the story again.  This may be interesting...
\par NL:\tab Yes, extremely.
\par YM:\tab ...you know, that he can't tell me b
ecause part of them went already, and part.  "But you know who went," I said, "tell me, are they still in Bergen-Belsen?  Are they off, are they away, where are they?"  So, he says, eh, he says.  So I told him, "Look, here is this desk.  I will break it t
o pieces and I will kill you here if you don't give me an answer.  Because my life isn't worth anything anyhow."  So, he got very, he got very, eh...
\par NL:\tab Disturbed.
\par YM:\tab ...disturbed by that, and told the girl to bring in the list.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab And told me that, no, my family is still in Bergen-Belsen, but they will be transferred, I don't know, to...
\par NL:\tab Switzerland.
\par YM:\tab ...Switzerland, with the second or third transport, whatever it was.
\par NL:\tab But they were out of Hungary.
\par YM:\tab They were out of Hungary; they were in Germany.  With this }{\i\fs24 Sondergruppe}{\fs24  [special group], as they called it at the time.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  Yes.
\par YM:\tab So, this kind of thing, you know, you can't talk even, even forty years later without eh, being very much...
\par NL:\tab Agitated.
\par YM:\tab Distur-, agi-, by it.  So, this is the information, and now, what happened after that.
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, could you just tell me a little more about Kasztner, because there is such a controversy...
\par YM:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab ...over his role.  How did you know that he was in charge of this special transport?
\par YM:\tab This Dr. Hershkowich, Boblyn Hershkowich [phonetic]...
\par NL:\tab Oh, he told you.
\par YM:\tab ...told me, "This man is in charge."
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab I know nothing about hi-, about it.
\par NL:\tab You didn't know his name before, earlier?
\par YM:\tab No, I'd never heard of him.
\par NL:\tab You'd never heard of him.
\par YM:\tab And I know very little, I knew Joel Brand very well, he was, he lived in Budapest, but he, Kasztner was really a newspaper man who lived somewhere in Rumania.
\par NL:\tab Cluj?
\par YM:\tab Cluj, ya, in the former Hungary, formerly Hungary.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm, yes.
\par YM:\tab So, eh, I really didn't know about him, and I, and I never saw, never heard of him.
\par NL:\tab What sort of impression did he make?  Of course...
\par YM:\tab It is...
\par NL:\tab ...he was your enemy [chuckles].
\par YM:\tab It is very hard to be, to be just.
\par NL:\tab Yeah.
\par YM:\tab And to give any, any description even about the man from whom you want to know...
\par NL:\tab Life and death.
\par YM:\tab Life and death, so to say.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab So, but this was a terrible, this was one, one of the most destructive d
ay, impressions, or, or occurrences in my life.  Why?  Because I saw up there, my piano was broken to pieces, that was, one leg of the piano was laying in one end of the music room, the so-called mus-, eh, I had a special music room, you know...
\par NL:\tab Uh huh.
\par YM:\tab ...where I had the musical library.  And so on.  And, and, and here I see my }{\i\fs24 family}{\fs24 , my, my }{\i\fs24 child}{\fs24 , my }{\i\fs24 wife}{\fs24 , my, eh...
\par NL:\tab Everything.
\par YM:\tab ...aren't here anymore.  So everything is gone.  And later on, eh, I didn't have a chance to speak to Dr. Kasztn
er later on, when I was, for instance, in Israel already and he was there too.  I always thought of it to go back, talk to the man, and see, }{\i\fs24 Ma tuvu shel hibor zu}{\fs24 
?  What kind of a person, I never got to it.  Maybe in the back of my mind I didn't want to really, to go.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Most probably, psychologically, eh.
\par NL:\tab It's understandable.
\par YM:\tab ...eh, probably, I can understand it, but the fact is that I spoke about it, spoke about it, spoke, I will go and see, eh, what was his first name, eh, Kasztner, eh...
\par NL:\tab Rezs\'f6.
\par YM:\tab Rezs\'f6.  I'm going to see Rezs\'f6, talk to him, }{\i\fs24 mama-lushen, pushit}{\fs24 
, [simple mother language] ask and see, see who is he that he could be such a murderer.  And when I come to him and the girl tells him who I am, I, not that I was a bigger }{\i\fs24 yichuss}{\fs24 
 [status] than anybody else, but that he's a, that he was able to, to, throw me out, so to say, and not even talk to me.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab So, but I never got to him face to face.
\par NL:\tab Were there indeed German guards in his office?  Could you see some surveillance?
\par YM:\tab I didn't see, I didn't see, I didn't see, but, his office was on the second floor, and down-, downstairs--why, I don't know, most probably there were other German agencies or something--there was a Hungarian guard.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab And, of course, I went there saying that I live in the house, a Hungarian, I don't know, petty officer on furlough, so, so I just go home, and no one knew where I'm going, but this is what happened.
\par NL:\tab Were there other Jews trying to see him?  Were you aware of...
\par YM:\tab I know of none.
\par NL:\tab ...pressure on him?
\par YM:\tab I know of none.  But most probably there were, and this is why he was so extremely sensitive and refused.  Before he found out what it is.
