\par NL:\tab This is a continuation of our interview with Cantor Yehuda Mandel, June 4th, interviewing.  You were about to say something about Joel Brand's wife.
\par YM:\tab Joel Brand's wife was an extremely capable, smart woman.  And I think she would have been more capable to do the work which was assigned to Joel than Joel himself.
\par NL:\tab More sophisticated.
\par YM:\tab More sophisticated and with more, with more }{\i\fs24 chutzpah}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab Because it required a tremendous amount of }{\i\fs24 chutzpah}{\fs24 , which he had, but not in the right directio
n somehow.  He wasn't the right person for the job.  This is my opinion and I don't, I wasn't there and I don't know, unfortunately, the history and the facts well enough to make--to judge.  This is just my opinion.  Now, eh, but we have to come back, I t
hink, to, where I left off.
\par NL:\tab Yes, yes, we do indeed.  You were saying that Kasztner finally told you that your family was still in Bergen-Belsen.
\par YM:\tab In Bergen-Belsen, and they will be sent over to Switzerland with the first transport.  We waited, as you know, these months went by.
\par NL:\tab Where did you stay, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab I went to stay with, in this }{\i\fs24 geschuetzte}{\fs24  [protected] }{\i\fs24 Haus}{\fs24 
, so to say, the guarded, the protected house.  Once here, once there, I got this document which is the runner's, eh, runner's document to bring messages from one place to the other, and as you know, as you remember, these documents were given out with th
e knowledge of, of, poor, what's his name?
\par NL:\tab Wallenberg.
\par YM:\tab Wallenberg.  And I was in the, under the protection of the Switzer consulate, eh, so this was, this was the thing with which I was, which was, I was going around.
\par NL:\tab Did we make a copy of this?
\par YM:\tab I think you did.
\par NL:\tab These are among the things you gave me.
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab Oh fine.
\par YM:\tab Yes.  But I of course had falsified papers.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab That I am a Hungarian soldier here on, eh, on, eh, wounded, and here on furlough, and so on and so forth.  But those, those papers I destroyed after the Russians...
\par NL:\tab Came in.
\par YM:\tab Abbreviated, eh, freed Budapest, so to say, because I was afraid many people were taken into custody for this kind of course.
\par NL:\tab Of course.
\par YM:\tab Being you worked for the Hungarians, and you were this and this, you know, it wasn't important it should be true, it was important if someone found out.  You know.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab It was very dangerous.  But this was what I carried around.  I was dressed up as a, as a peasant, and I had this in my pocket for where I went, people knew that I am, I am official of the, of Switzer, eh, consulate or delegation.
\par NL:\tab And Wallenberg gave you this?
\par YM:\tab Wallenberg's office.
\par NL:\tab Wallenberg's office gave you this.
\par YM:\tab Gave it to me.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  And so you were able to get meals there?
\par YM:\tab No, don't think of meals as you have a meal you sit down.
\par NL:\tab Bread.
\par YM:\tab But whatever there was,
\par NL:\tab Ya.
\par YM:\tab Whatever there was, we shared.  If it was a cup of tea, it was that.  If it was a piece of bread, it was that.  
If we could get in somehow, through one of our men, eh, some food, real food, it was cooked, and our people prepared it.  There was a time, for instance, we couldn't cook, because there was no water.  The water level was so low that there was no possibili
ty to cook.  So, that is the way it went by.
\par NL:\tab About how many people were there in your house?
\par YM:\tab In that, in that one house I would say there were about close to 300.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  And this we slept like sardines but we...
\par NL:\tab You were safe.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  We, more or less, we were safe.
\par NL:\tab More or less.
\par YM:\tab And these months like the rest of November, December, up to January when Budapest was occupied by the, or rather, freed...
\par NL:\tab Liberated.
\par YM:\tab ...as they call, liberated by the Russians, eh, that's the way we, we really lived.  
\par NL:\tab Can you say a little more about those months, Cantor?  Did you have contact with other Jews in similar houses?
\par YM:\tab A lot.
\par NL:\tab A lot.
\par YM:\tab A lot, because I was one of the people as this }{\i\fs24 Fut\'e1rigazoly\'e1ny}{\fs24  means as you see here, }{\i\fs24 Eilbot}{\fs24 --}{\i\fs24 Eilbotenausweis}{\fs24 .  This is the, the, eh, document for a runner.
\par NL:\tab Messenger.
\par YM:\tab What?  Ya, messenger, from one place to the other.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab I went to Wallenberg's office, I saw him...
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab ...once in awhile.  I spoke to him a word or two.  Of course, there was no time.  I got a pack of, of documents from him to take it to this place, to that place, and that's where I went.
\par NL:\tab In other words, you were able to give other Jews papers that enabled them to be protected?
\par YM:\tab Yes.  And we had our people there, and they filled in the names and gave it a number, and it became an official document.  In some cases these, eh, }{\i\fs24 Nyilas}{\fs24 ...
\par NL:\tab Arrow Cross.
\par YM:\tab Arrow Cross, eh, youngsters, respected it, and in some cases they didn't.  They just took them away.
\par NL:\tab I see.  So Budapest was still under the control of the Arrow Cross...
\par YM:\tab Ya.  Oh yes, all these months, all these months.
\par NL:\tab In, eh, November, December, these months.
\par YM:\tab That means about two weeks in November, the whole December, and the whole January, and those were terrible months.  The worst anyone, because you never knew when you were on the street, if a youngster of 12 or 13 or 15 had just a, a...
\par NL:\tab A whim.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  A whim, to, to kill you, he did, no problem.  And he wasn't, he wasn't taken to give account for it, why he did it, what he did it, as long as it was a Jew, no problem.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab Now, during this time, maybe there is one outstanding occurrence and you've probably, eh, seen that in, in the Brand book, where we dressed up as Hungarian gendarmerie.  I was one of them.
\par NL:\tab You were one of them.
\par YM:\tab With them, and we went to the, prisons and we took out, altogether, close to 300 people.  We, we cursed them, and pushed them, and hollered at them, and all that, but we told them quietly, "You are being taken, you are being rescued."
\par NL:\tab Ohhh my.
\par YM:\tab This may be...
\par NL:\tab Oh, that's extraordinary.
\par YM:\tab This is extraordinary.  This is a...
\par NL:\tab This is a prison in Budapest?
\par YM:\tab There was a so-called }{\i\fs24 g\'fcta }{\fs24  folkhouse [phonetic] where they gathered from all places the people who they wanted to...
\par NL:\tab Deport.
\par YM:\tab ...deport.  To march.
\par NL:\tab An assembly point.
\par YM:\tab Ya, ya, an assembly point.  And we took them out.  We came 
with false papers and we, documentation and all that.  And there was one of them, this young man, eh, what was his name?  He became later consul of Israel in one of the countries.  I don't remember his name anymore.  But his name is mentioned in...
\par NL:\tab In Brand's book.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  In Brand's book.  He was our commander and he was...
\par NL:\tab These were Zionists?
\par YM:\tab Ya, all Zionist people.
\par NL:\tab All Zionists.  I see.
\par YM:\tab And he had so much }{\i\fs24 azis}{\fs24  [impudence], [chuckles], he had so much, really }{\i\fs24 chutzpah}{\fs24 , that...
\par NL:\tab Courage.
\par YM:\tab Courage.  Nothing could stop him.
\par NL:\tab Daring.
\par YM:\tab Ya, daring.  And we hollered at the Jews and cursed them and what, and quietly we were telling them that, "You are being taken out of here and places elsewhere."
\par NL:\tab Oh my.  That's, that happens, yes.
\par YM:\tab I, I just can't talk about it without, without getting goose pimples, you know?
\par NL:\tab I too, of course.  This was in December?
\par YM:\tab In, in, in December, probably, or January.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab The worst time.
\par NL:\tab And where were they then taken?
\par YM:\tab Fifty here...
\par NL:\tab Into these protected homes.
\par YM:\tab We didn't take 300 at once, we took 50, 40, 50, whatever there was in that so-called }{\i\fs24 g\'fcte}{\fs24  [phonetic], eh, gathering eh, prison, you know.
\par NL:\tab Assembly place.
\par YM:\tab Assembly place.  We took them out, and that 
happened three, four, or five times.  We had all these, heh, eh, shields, from, what the, what the gendarmerie, the Hungarian gendarmerie used to wear, you know, while doing their thing, their killing the Jews.  I lived through, eh, Ujvid\'e9
k, that means Novi Sad.
\par NL:\tab Novi Sad.
\par YM:\tab You know, the }{\i\fs24 harigah}{\fs24  [massacre] in Novi Sad, I lived that, through.  I was at the Danube.  And I told you I think already what happened there.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab Now, to come, to go on, back further, when finally Budapest was liberated by the Russians, it took a day or so before I, eh, I had a }{\i\fs24 yeshivah}{\fs24  friend, }{\i\fs24 yeshivah}{\fs24 
 friend of mine, Dr. Breslauer, who became the emissary of Czechoslovakian affairs in Budapest, and he gave me papers to go to Czechoslovakia, because I wanted to get in touch with my family.
\par NL:\tab You hadn't heard, of course, from them.
\par YM:\tab Not a thing about them.  Just what I heard from an opinion--no, what, the fir-, I went to Czechoslovakia, I couldn't get out any telegram, anything.  A week or two later, that means in
 February, probably, or the beginning of March, we were told that a repat- repatriation affair will be taking place from Switzerland, the people who were taken by Kasztner's group to Switzerland, will be transported back to Hungary, and I was waiting that
 my wife will return.
\par NL:\tab But you were then in Czechoslovakia.
\par YM:\tab I, I, no...
\par NL:\tab You went back.
\par YM:\tab I was in Czechoslovakia for a short while.  I came back to Budapest and waited.
\par NL:\tab What about the Russian occupation?  Did you feel the sting of that?
\par YM:\tab They, they did not interfere with me personally.
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab I know many people who, for one reason or another, or even without a reason, were tak-, were...
\par NL:\tab Arrested.
\par YM:\tab ...arrested, and never came back, or came back in a half a year or a year, or what not.  But personally I did not feel, first of all, I spoke the language fluently, and if I got into a }{\i\fs24 hoddenwieden}{\fs24 
 [phonetic], for instance, once, I walked, eh, from my house to the next block, let's say, and I saw that two Russian soldiers, eh, ar
e coming in my direction.  And as soon as we would have passed each other, they started to walk back.  One was in front of me, and one was in the back of me.  And I was foolish enough to wear my watch.  So, as it was customary in those days, [unclear] sha
ll see, they had already fifteen watches on their arm, but they wanted to have your watch, too.  So, he says, "Give the watch."  I said, I didn't give it to him right away, and maybe that was foolish, why, I don't know, but I had }{\i\fs24 chutzpah }{
\fs24 enough maybe, I was educated in these actions, you know, and I told him in Russian, "Look, you don't have the right to take this watch from me, but I will give it to you, }{\i\fs24 if}{\fs24 
 you will give me your number and you will tell me your name.  Show me your documentation.  I don't w
ant, I know you don't have the right, but you give me your name, and I will go from here directly to the commander of the Russian army here in Budapest, and you will hear from me later."
\par NL:\tab Oh ho, they disappeared [laughs].
\par YM:\tab They disappeared.  This was one experience.
\par NL:\tab Well.
\par YM:\tab Another
 experience was you know in labor camp, we didn't have, we got any any, any news, any piece of paper, any, anything, we couldn't read.  So in the evenings, nights, when we laid down already on our bunks, on the little bit of straw or whatever was on the f
loor, we, we had those automatic, eh, flashlights, where you have to, it had a little battery inside, and if you pushed it hard enough, it gave you a little light.  So, I had one of these little...
\par NL:\tab Flashlights.
\par YM:\tab Flashlights, and a Russian boy, fifteen years old, was the Russian guard, came to me and told me, "Give me that!"  He saw it in my hand.  Saw it.  So, I didn't want to make a big }{\i\fs24 schpiel}{\fs24 
 [to do] or, he was a child, so to say, I didn't want, eh, I gave it to him.
\par NL:\tab You gave it to him.
\par YM:\tab This happened, and this happened with drinks and watches and...
\par NL:\tab Jewelry.
\par YM:\tab ...whatever they wanted.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Whatever they wanted.  So these are the...
\par NL:\tab You weren't, you weren't hurt by them.
\par YM:\tab No, and these are probably the occurrences which a
nyone who was occupied by a force, by--I had another experience, for instance, a friend of mine whose father already was a board member of my temple, came to me after, after we were, we were already freed by the Hungarians, by the...
\par NL:\tab Russians.
\par YM:\tab Russians.  That he has material to produce, I don't know, how many hundreds of kilo of soap.  And the city was dying of dirt, and, and, and, and, filth, and...
\par NL:\tab Disease.
\par YM:\tab And disease.  And he said he will produce it on his own, for his own money.  So I, 
"What really do you want from me?"  "You speak Russian so well.  Please come with me to the commander of the city."  I went with him and we sat down and, when I told the commander, it was, I think, the associate commander or something like that, I told th
i
s general what my friend wants, he will give half without charge to the government, but half he wants to sell on the open market.  So the answer of the, of the soldier--of the general was, "Tell your friend that I already called in two soldiers.  They wil
l
 be given a few minutes.  The pants he is wearing aren't his either.  We didn't come here as friends.  We came here as an occupying force, and, therefore, whatever he has he will have to go with these people, show him where it is, give us the material, pr
epare it as he wanted, and we will take it."
\par NL:\tab Mmm.  Confiscate everything.
\par YM:\tab This was their attitude.
\par NL:\tab Their mentality.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  So I'm not wondering now about the little boy of 15 or 16 who came and wanted my flashlight.  But to come back to this, 
many, many people came back from Switzerland, in buses and so on, and from them, particularly one family with whom I was very friendly, came back and gave me a report about my family, from the, for the first time I heard from them probably it was March, o
r...
\par NL:\tab The first time in how long?
\par YM:\tab I left Hungary the last time probably in Ju-, May, May the 30th.  We just spoke about it this last Sunday with my son, and he was there, so he remembers.  Because--and he brought me an article from someone who was in
 the same city at the same time.  It was May the 29th or 30th of 1944 I left.  Now, probably I saw my family the day when the Germans marched into Hungary, that was the 19th...
\par NL:\tab The 19th of March.
\par YM:\tab ...of March.  From the 19th of March to about a year
, a year in space, I didn't hear from my family, I didn't know these things what I mentioned before occurred during that time.  I got the information that my family is in Switzerland.  Then I went illegally the second and the third time to Czechoslovakia,
 then I could already send telegrams, I wrote a letter which I sent,  eh, to, to, eh, what was it, }{\i\fs24 Sur Montreux}{\fs24 \endash 
that's where my family was--and my wife, because of her profession--she was a teacher--she got together 40 children and under the guidance of the, of the Switzer Jewish, eh...
\par NL:\tab Welfare.
\par YM:\tab ...Welfare Board, she made a class, a school out of them, and taught them for, I don't know how long.
\par NL:\tab How long was she in Bergen-Belsen?
\par YM:\tab She was in Bergen-Belsen from the 30th of May, we just calculated it this week, 30th of May to about, eh, December, probably.  December.
\par NL:\tab Under harsh conditions.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  Under, under, under Bergen-Belsen conditions.  What more can I tell you?  But they were still not as bad as the ones who were just in the, in the concentration camps.
\par NL:\tab So they still, a special, special continu-
\par YM:\tab Under separate, was a }{\i\fs24 Sondergruppe}{\fs24  as they called it, }{\i\fs24 Sondergruppe}{\fs24 .  They were, of course, they had guards around and all that, but they got some food, they got some care, eh...
\par NL:\tab They weren't killed.
\par YM:\tab They weren't killed.  I remember that this boy who is now in Israel, a very fine y
oung man who my wife rescued, had an infection of the middle ear.  And one of our professors, who was also in this group, Dr. Polachek, was given permission to go in with, he was a laryngologist, an outstanding man, to be taken by a German guard or whatev
er to the town somewhere to a hospital where he performed the operation.  The child had a 103\u778\'b0
  fever and all that, was brought back, and the child today, thank God, has three beautiful children, and so on.  So these kind of things which, which had transpired in those days is hard, very hard even to remember or to describe.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  Can you just add another point, eh, Cantor, um, did your wife, um, have to make some special effort to get to Kasztner in order to be part of this special transport?  How did she negotiate that?
\par YM:\tab No, she did not.  My brother...
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab ...who was a rabbinical student at the time in the seminary, and, as I have told you before, he got his doctoral degree already with the yellow Star of David on his lapel, he was very active in the Zionist movement.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab So he, when these things were discussed, who shall be taken, a) he was there...
\par NL:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par YM:\tab ...and I don't know if he mentioned at all or not, but my friends who were there, like this Komoly, Otto, who was
 a very dear friend, I'm sure he thought of it just as well, not to leave Ella with the child, just when I am, I don't know where, leave her here, if there is a possibility to rescue them.  I don't think she had to negotiate too much.
\par NL:\tab So it was your brother who spoke, eh...
\par YM:\tab My brother was there, ah, he was in that committee or not, I don't know.
\par NL:\tab So it was not just Kasztner's decision.
\par YM:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab It was a joint decision.
\par YM:\tab No.  No.  No.  That was, that was a deci-, a deci-, it wasn't--probably the final decision was Kasztner's, but the suggestions, who should be taken, were given by the Zionist organization, by the leaders of the Zionist organization.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.  Yes, that's an interesting point.  Because many people think he did the whole, eh, he made the whole solution.
\par YM:\tab No.  I don't think anyone, that anyone went to Kasztner for, maybe the Rumanian settlement of the, of the...
\par NL:\tab Cluj.
\par YM:\tab Yes, the Cluj, around Cluj, but in Budapest, I don't think Kasztner carried that much weight, a), and 
secondly, I don't think anyone knew about Kasztner.  So if it was a case where, let's say just for the sake of argument, Ella Mandel was contacted, she wasn't contacted by Kasztner.  She was contacted by Komoly, by, by somebody else, no, there were fiftee
n, twenty, or twenty-five people on that board, and each had his friends, of course...
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab ...as it's impossible it shouldn't go like this.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  Of course.
\par YM:\tab Of course.
\par NL:\tab Of course.
\par YM:\tab And these people were thinking of each other, who were the people, who are really the leaders of the community; who can be, should be, rescued, because I don't think that, first of all, they had to have the money, I mean, let's be practical.

\par NL:\tab Yes, I was going to ask, do you know how much they had to pay?
\par YM:\tab They had to have the wealth.  I don't-, there wasn't a set.
\par NL:\tab There wasn't.
\par YM:\tab No.  Diamonds, and gold, and wedding rings, and dollars, and, eh, sterling from, from, [unclear].
\par NL:\tab Anything with asset value.
\par YM:\tab Anything of asset, of hard currency, hard value.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab That was taken.  And, and probably they got together millions and millions in value.  So, I don't think I was the one who had the amount of money or gold or diamonds, or whatnot, to, eh...
\par NL:\tab Ransom them.
\par YM:\tab ...to, to ransom them.  Eh, I had books, which weren't worth anything, as you see, eh, firewood, for firewood they were good, nothing else.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab So, eh...
\par NL:\tab So you made contact, and your wife conducted the school.
\par YM:\tab No.  She conducted the school there.  I never, I wrote to her, I tried to call her, I, eh, tried to, for her to get back to Hungary, because, on the 3rd of March is my birthday.
\par NL:\tab Ahhh.
\par YM:\tab Can you imagine?  And when we were liberated already, people from all kinds of companies came with pick and shovel and told me, "We will give you a gift for your birthday, and it will be we will clean the courtyard of the temple."
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par YM:\tab My temple was...
\par NL:\tab A shambles.
\par YM:\tab ...a shambles.  And, eh, it was th
e ghetto hospital, do I have to tell you more?  A stench, you couldn't go there, you couldn't get in there, the seats, the Rombach Temple is an art, a work of art, and all the seats were torn out, used for firewood, of course, and, and the...
\par NL:\tab Chandeliers.
\par YM:\tab ...the, the, the }{\i\fs24 cupola}{\fs24 
, the, top, was broken down, and when after we got together in March, and my comrades gave me this gift, I organized in my temple a rebuilding committee.  And that was in March/April.  And I got so much money, not I, I had a committee for that.
\par NL:\tab Yes, for the funds.
\par YM:\tab For the funds.  With }{\i\fs24 Slichot}{\fs24  services in the fall were already performed...
\par NL:\tab In the sanctuary.
\par YM:\tab In the sanctuary, in the temple.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab And I thought everything goes in the right direction.
\par NL:\tab Now, the Russians didn't disturb you.
\par YM:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab Interesting.
\par YM:\tab The only difficulties we had was to get material to rebuild the dome, for instance, what needed another--a lot of iron bars and whatnot, so we had a man by the name on our board at the temp
le by the name Hagadush [phonetic], who was in this line, and he got us all the material we needed for the dome of the temple.  Another one got us material for the wood part, a third one, it wasn't rebuilt as it was once upon a time, but it was rebuilt, a
nd }{\i\fs24 Slichos}{\fs24  we could say already, and that was a great achievement.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab The choir was reestablished.  Everything, I thought, everything is fine.  Not only that, but the chief rabbi of Hungary was Dr. Havashi, who suggested to me at the time to go 
into the Hungarian army as a chaplain, maybe I won't have any trouble anymore because I speak the language and I was born in Hungary and all that, he didn't know, that's another story.
\par NL:\tab Well, who knows.
\par YM:\tab But, he tried.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab But his son became, after the war, when the so-called Hungarian government was already organized, the Russians were still there, but they didn't show themselves, I mean the Hungarian government...
\par NL:\tab Took over.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  Eh, he became the chief chaplain of the Armed Forces,
 and was a very dear friend of mine and offered me a position in a high-ranking, as a high-ranking officer in his, eh, off-, in his department, because I had so much experience in labor camps, so he said, "There are }{\i\fs24 agunot}{\fs24 
 [abandoned wives] and all kinds of questions, and you will be the one to organize it the proper way."
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab "You can stay as chief cantor of your temple.  You can stay with the congregation.  Stay here."  So I wrote all this to my wife, but she just became so disillusioned and disg
usted with Hungary, where she grew up, and she was born, and she knew the language, that she just did not want to come back.  I remember the High Holy Days went by and, eh, she prepared for Israel directly.  She never came back...
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab ...neither as a repatriate nor as a private person, nor anything.  She was a great Zionist, to begin with.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab And she wanted to go to be a }{\i\fs24 chalutzah}{\fs24  in, in Palestine.
\par NL:\tab Excuse me another minute now.
\par YM:\tab Yes, sure.
\par NL:\tab Were you able to go back to your apartment, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab No.  No.
\par NL:\tab Where did you live?
\par YM:\tab But I got, I had a very dear friend of mine, he was a lawyer by profession, may he rest in peace, Dr. Deutsch, who, we were close, very close friends, who told me, "Now you are not going to repair 
that broken down apartment up there.  Here on the third floor is the apartment of this antisemite who ran out, who ran away.  You move in there.  What will be later, we will see.  But in the mean-," and that's where I lived.
\par NL:\tab That's where you lived.
\par YM:\tab I, I lived one, eh, floor below, and gave space, I was by myself, all the people who came little by little, I had two sister-in-laws came from Auschwitz, they stayed with me for a while, other people who needed, eh, a place where...
\par NL:\tab Housing.
\par YM:\tab ...a place where--housing, they lived there.  And my sister-in-law, who is now in Israel, and her sister, they lived there.  I had a, a, not a\'85
\par NL:\tab A }{\i\fs24 kibbutz}{\fs24  [chuckles].
\par YM:\tab Ya, a }{\i\fs24 kibbutz}{\fs24  like, }{\i\fs24 Kibbutz galiyot}{\fs24 .  And, eh, the end, we corresponded back, I wr
ote, rather, I didn't correspond because I didn't get an answer.  The first letter I got from my wife was already, was when she was already in Bari, South Italy.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.  She really had made a firm decision.
\par YM:\tab Firm decision.  She was on her way.  I got-
\par NL:\tab With your son.
\par YM:\tab Ya, with my son.  And the other boy.
\par NL:\tab The other boy.
\par YM:\tab And, eh, the letter read, "I read all your letters.  I wrote to you.  I hope you have received it.  What with it all, my final decision is not to step any more on Hungarian soil."  Her parents, her brothers, her brothers-in-law, her...
\par NL:\tab All perished.
\par YM:\tab All perished.  So, it's understandable.  And she walked out of that magnificent apartment, of that elegant apartment, a little castle of art, she walked out with a sack on her back...
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab ...with the two children.  So you can imagine how she felt.  And she said, "After all this, I hope you got my letters gradually, but in the meantime, I want you to remember, I am with [unclear] son, plus [phonetic], so, and s
o," and I knew who it is, and that was the first letter I received.  Can you imagine?
\par NL:\tab And you were, of course, divided about this.
\par YM:\tab Right.  And I decided, definitely she said not to go back to that blood-soaked country anymore.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab "And I'm going to Israel."
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab "I will let you know where I am.  And if you want to, we can unite again in Israel."  So you can imagine what, what that, what that meant, at the time.  That was, and finally, took a little, took time, you know, because I ha
d to, we started the High Holy Days, there was }{\i\fs24 Rosh Hashanah}{\fs24  and }{\i\fs24 Yom Kippur}{\fs24  and }{\i\fs24 Succot}{\fs24 , and }{\i\fs24 Hoshana Rabba}{\fs24 
, and everything was prepared for me to stay there.  And I started already to work with this Dr. Ferencz Hadashi, to, eh, maybe help people the time being in an inoffi-, an, eh, unofficial capacity but help them, eh...\sect }\sectd 
